ase_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"Evan Aagaard\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5233:\"<p><strong><a href=\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/10/18/power-of-the-people/57982_144248632278051_144247865611461_198761_7504073_n/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-1035\"><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1035\" title=\"57982_144248632278051_144247865611461_198761_7504073_n\" src=\"http://theseednetwork.com/wp-content/uploads/57982_144248632278051_144247865611461_198761_7504073_n5.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a>True story:</strong> I was waiting for a flight at the Kelowna airportÂ the other day when I decided to make a last minute change to my returnÂ date. I called upÂ <a href=\"http://www.flightcentre.ca\">Flightcentre.ca</a> (with whom I made the booking) and wasÂ immediately connected with the agent who originally handled myÂ booking, I believe he picked up after the first ring.</p>\n<p>His name isÂ Gordon. I requested to change the date, Gordon happilyÂ accommodated with aÂ flurry of quick taps,Â informedÂ me of the additional surcharge (lessÂ than I expected) and wished me a happy flight. Total talk time fromÂ dial to disconnect: 1 minute 38 seconds. Â The service was fast,Â succinct and delivered with a warm and familiar cheer as though heÂ knew me as an old friend. I&#8217;ve spoken with other Flightcentre.caÂ agents in the past and they&#8217;ve given me a similar level of care andÂ familiarity.</p>\n<p>A funny smile crept across my face and I realized I wasÂ beaming with that bemused afterglow that comes on whenÂ things go exactly your way and the service or product you&#8217;ve payedÂ for actually delivers on all of its promises (sometimes described in the businessesÂ world as the Holy Grail of good customer relationshipÂ management).</p>\n<p>Using my iPhone (and the airport&#8217;s free wi-fi) IÂ jump on to Facebook and look up <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/FlightCentreCA\">FlightCentre.ca&#8217;s page</a>. I find itÂ immediately. They have 8500+ likes. I not only like their page but IÂ leave a positive comment on their wall:</p>\n<blockquote><p><em>I&#8217;ve had a great experience, super friendly customerÂ service and no hassle bookings &#8211; thanks to Gordon at the Vernon</em>Â <em>office.</em></p></blockquote>\n<p>I sign off and board my flight. Total transactionÂ time from phone call to Facebook feedback: under 5Â minutes.</p>\n<p>(Anecdote&#8217;s Caveat)Â I have NEVERÂ given positive customer feedback before to any company, about anyÂ service, product or experience. EVER.</p>\n<p>Why?</p>\n<p>Well it&#8221;s not thatÂ I haven&#8217;t been treated well before in my various dealings with theconsumer world. Certainly the opportunity has existed in the past, mentioning that helpful store cashier to her manager, dropping off aÂ heart-felt note in the company suggestion box, emailing the clientÂ support account etc etc. I guess the channels available to me neverÂ piqued my interest nor the time delay and murkiness of what actuallyÂ happens to my correspondence once it&#8217;sÂ received. But aÂ social media response offered me an entirely different avenue.</p>\n<p>TheÂ <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/FlightCentreCA\">flightcentre.caÂ Facebook page</a> gave me a forum where I could notÂ only express my satisfaction of the company&#8217;s service but publiclyÂ reward the specific agent who helped me (remember people do businessÂ with people not companies). Perhaps the most compelling aspect of theÂ entire transaction was how easy andÂ accessibleÂ it was. I was alreadyÂ going on Facebook, checking up on theÂ <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/FlightCentreCA\" target=\"_blank\">Flightcentre.caÂ page</a>Â was just an afterthought. They had presence in a social space I wasÂ using anyway and that made it incrediblyÂ convenient (for me) toÂ translate my positive experience into valuable customer feedback forÂ them.</p>\n<p>Now here&#8217;s where it gets really interesting: when I went back to check on the <a href=\"http://www.facebook.com/FlightCentreCA\" target=\"_blank\">FlightcentreÂ page</a>Â later I discovered another user, one who had not had such a positiveÂ experience, had left aÂ disparagingÂ comment on my post accusing me ofÂ working for Flightcentre and calling my positive comment bogus. IÂ engaged her and explained that I was simply a satisfied customer fromÂ my own personal experience. Maybe she did have a bad transaction,Â it&#8217;s really not my concern. I only know what happened to me. Â But inÂ this context I am now not only leaving a great response for theÂ company but actively defending it from its detractors within a publicÂ forum. The day before I couldn&#8221;t have given two licks about Flightcentre, now I&#8217;m acting as its surrogate PR champion.</p>\n<p>AreÂ you beginning to see the importance of maintaing a strong Â PR presenceÂ within the social media sphere? I am perhaps the world&#8217;s mostÂ apathetic consumer and yet here I am actively participating in aÂ public conversation available to all my friends and the thousands ofÂ people who officially like this company, generating the sort ofÂ word-of-mouth headwind most companies would die for, and it didn&#8217;tÂ cost Flightcentre a dime!</p>\n<p>Good customer service + active (and savvy) socialÂ media presence = self-generating marketing powerhouse.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:36:\"http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/\";a:1:{s:10:\"commentRss\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:67:\"http://theseednetwork.com/blog/2011/10/18/power-of-the-people/feed/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base